    "passage": "In studying the diaries of nineteenth-century factory workers, historian Mei Lin Chao challenges a long-standing assumption: that industrial laborers experienced their grueling routines as an unbroken monotony. Chao notes that the workers' own accounts are punctuated by detailed descriptions of small variations—a malfunctioning loom, an unfamiliar supervisor, a change in the weather seeping through the factory walls. Far from registering their days as identical, the workers catalogued difference obsessively. Chao argues that this attentiveness was not incidental but strategic: by parsing minute distinctions, the workers preserved a sense of time's movement that the rhythms of mechanized production threatened to erase.",
