    "type": "Cross-Text Connections",
    "difficulty": "hard",
    "passage": "Text 1\nThe explosive spread of Martin Luther's ideas after 1517 is inseparable from the printing press. Within a few years, hundreds of thousands of pamphlets bearing his arguments circulated across the German lands. Without this machinery of rapid, cheap reproduction, Luther's challenge would likely have remained, like earlier dissents, a local quarrel swiftly contained. The press did not merely carry the Reformation; it made the Reformation possible.\n\nText 2\nPrinting presses had been operating in Europe for over half a century before Luther, yet they produced no comparable upheaval. What distinguished the 1520s was not the technology but a population already primed by economic resentment of Rome, by disputes over clerical privilege, and by a hunger for vernacular scripture. The presses found a public that was waiting; they did not create it.",
