    "passage": "Text 1\nEmily Dickinson's dashes are not accidents of penmanship but a deliberate notation. They function as a kind of musical score—marking pauses of varying length, signaling hesitation, and severing words from the grammar that would otherwise domesticate them. To regularize her punctuation, as her nineteenth-century editors did, is to silence an essential instrument of her art.\n\nText 2\nWe should be cautious about reading too much intention into Dickinson's dashes. Her surviving manuscripts show the same loose, sloping strokes in her grocery lists and casual notes as in her poems. What modern critics elevate into a sophisticated prosodic system may be nothing more than an habitual flourish of the hand—one that posthumous admirers, hunting for genius, have invested with meanings the poet never assigned.",
