    "prompt": "A bag contains 6 red chips and 4 blue chips. Two chips are drawn at random, one after the other, without replacement. Given that the second chip drawn is red, what is the probability that the first chip drawn was blue?",
    "format": "mc",
    "choices": [
      "4/9",
      "2/5",
      "2/3",
      "4/15"
    ],
    "answer": 0,
    "explanation": "Conditioning on 'second chip is red' restricts the sample space. P(2nd red) = 6/10 = 3/5 (overall). P(1st blue AND 2nd red) = (4/10)(6/9) = 4/15. So P(1st blue | 2nd red) = (4/15)/(3/5) = 4/9. The tempting 2/5 just gives P(first blue) and ignores the condition; 2/3 = 6/9 is P(second red | first blue), the reverse conditional; 4/15 is the joint probability, not the conditional probability."
